Taken from *Bhagavad Gita *(Chapter 7, Verse 5) this verse translates to:

*Lord Krishna* gives sermon to Arjun who is bewildered. This eightfold
(Earth, water, fire, air, ether, mind, intellect and personality) natural
existence is sublime or much inferior, to a superior energy of mine, which
takes form of different living entities and permeates in constant struggle
with material nature. That energy including their struggles sustains the
universe. O mighty-armed Arjuna, you should know that. In other words-
Whatever is happening is as per my wish.

There exists a Supreme Being in this infinite, eternal, and changeless
universe, from which all living beings originate and eventually merge back
into. This profound truth encompasses everything that has happened, is
happening, and will happen. Analogous to a wave emerging from the ocean,
Brahman emanates from this Supreme Being, and just as a wave merge into the
ocean, similarly, the Supreme Being is one, and the universe is a
manifestation of it. This is undoubtedly Brahman.

God and original nature (God =3D animate element, original nature =3D
unconscious element) stand as contrasting forces. The original nature,
illuminated by the divine power of God, gives rise to qualities. Through
mutual interaction, these qualities manifest various forms (bodies). This
divine power is known as Maya; hence God is referred to as Mayavati.

We all can identify as *Sanatani*. Sanatan is not a religion but a concept,
a way of life, a rebellion against rudeness, barbarity, and brutality.
*Sanatan* is the transition from narrow selfishness to greater altruism,
emphasizing a stronger sense of duty than rights. It signifies the
realization of self-freedom from physical, divine, and material bondages,
guiding life from the bondage of birth and death towards eternal peace.

A *Sanatani *engages in rituals to establish balance in the entire
universe, performing Yagya, idol worship, and organizing life in a
harmonious manner.

*Sanatan* involves worshiping earth, water, air, sky, fire, mountains,
trees, animals, and birds, believing that God resides in every particle of
creation. *Sanatani* embraces the concept of

*"Sarve Bhavan tum Sukhnah Sarve Santu Niramaya."*


*Thanks & Regards*
*Archana Bharat Vanshi*

